The '''Cultural Properties of Mozambique''' are protected and promoted in accordance with Law 10/88 of 1988 concerning tangible and [[Intangible cultural heritage|intangible]] properties relating to the cultural heritage of [[Mozambique]] (''bens materiais e imateriais do patrim√≥nio cultural mo√ßambicano'').<ref name="UNESCO">{{cite web |url=http://www.unesco.org/culture/natlaws/media/pdf/mozambique/mozambique_loi1088_pororof.pdf |title=Lei no. 10/88 |trans-title=Law no 10/88 |language=Portuguese |publisher=[[UNESCO]] |accessdate=8 May 2012}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.legisambiente.gov.mz/index.php?option=com_docman&task=cat_view&gid=30 |title=Portal de Legisla√ß√£o Ambiental de Mo√ßambique |trans-title=Portal of Environmental Legislation of Mozambique |language=Portuguese |publisher=Ministry of Coordination of Environmental Affairs |accessdate=8 May 2012 |deadurl=yes |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120727030844/http://www.legisambiente.gov.mz/index.php?option=com_docman&task=cat_view&gid=30 |archivedate=27 July 2012 |df= }}</ref> Article 3 defines eight classes of movable cultural properties and four classes of immovable cultural properties: monuments (''monumentos''), groups of buildings (''conjuntos os grupos de edif√≠cios''), sites (''locais ou sitios''), and natural elements (''elementos naturais''); those classed as ''patrim√≥nio cultural'' are of exceptional [[Values (heritage)|significance]] and are afforded special state protection.<ref name="UNESCO"/>
