[[File:Hoxton.jpg|thumb|right]] The '''Hoxton knot''',<ref name=NYO/> '''Chelsea knot''',<ref name=DT8>{{citation |title=How should men wear a scarf? |journal=[[The Daily Telegraph]] | url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/news/uknews/1540641/How-should-men-wear-a-scarf.html |author=Caroline Davies |date=12 Apr 2008 }}</ref> '''French loop''',<ref name=DT10>{{citation |title=A man shall be defined by his scarf |journal=[[The Daily Telegraph]] | url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/news/features/8174481/A-man-shall-be-defined-by-his-scarf.html |author=Harry de Quetteville |date=2 Dec 2010}}</ref> '''Parisian scarf knot'''<ref>{{citation |page=40 |title=A gentleman gets dressed up |author=John Bridges, Bryan Curtis |year=2003 |isbn=978-1-4016-0111-9}}</ref> or '''Snug Tug'''<ref>{{citation |title=Tying me up in knots |date=31 October 2006 |journal=[[The Guardian]] |author=Julie Bindel |url=https://www.theguardian.com/commentisfree/2006/oct/31/tyingmeupinknots}}</ref> is a method of arranging a [[scarf]] about the neck. The scarf is doubled back and placed around the neck. The tails of the scarf are then pulled through the U-bend of the doubling to secure them, as with a [[cow hitch|cow hitch or lark's head]].
The knot is popular with stylish men like [[David Beckham]] who frequent fashionable districts of London such as [[Hoxton]] and [[Chelsea, London|Chelsea]].<ref name=NYO>{{citation |url=http://www.observer.com/2007/03/the-smug-tug/ |author= Nicole Brydson |year=2007 |journal=[[New York Observer]] |title=The Smug Tug}}</ref> The style is also commonly used by [[outside broadcasting|outside broadcasters]] from the [[BBC]] as it is warm and tidy.<ref name=DT10/> It may be controversial though, as some commentators opine that knotting a scarf is less manly than just draping it around the neck or throwing the ends casually over the shoulder.<ref>{{citation |url=https://www.theguardian.com/commentisfree/2007/jan/26/post1000 |title=Tied up in knots - Traditional, macho, metrosexual or just a bit chilly - is the way in which a man wears his scarf really that telling? |author=Paul MacInnes |journal=[[The Guardian]] |date=26 January 2007}}</ref>
==See also== *[[Snood (headgear)#Football|Snood]] &ndash; the snug, tubular comforter which generated similar controversy when worn by football players.
